description:
Geoffrey Keezer runs through some exercises to help get your left hand as strong as your right.

Check out Geoffrey's course, Advanced Jazz Piano Concepts, at https://www.openstudiojazz.com/advanced-jazz-piano-concepts

=====================================================

(lively jazz music)

- Hey this is Geoffrey Keezer for 2 Minute Jazz.  I'm gonna talk about how to build up your left hand so your left hand can play all the same stuff your right hand can.  I get asked a lot of times, you know, "Hey, I'm a right-handed pianist, how do I build up my left hand to be strong?"  And the answer really is very simple.  It's literally practice the same things with your left hand that you do with your right.  For example, if you've transcribed a solo, by a pianist or a horn player, and you're getting that under your belt, and you're shredding with your right hand.  Well, then if your left hand isn't able to play to the same speed slow it down with a metronome, but start slow, but build it up.  For example, this Bud Powell solo on "Parisian Thoroughfare."

(lively jazz music)

Right, that's the first 16 bars just practice maybe the first 8 bars with your left hand alone.

(slow tempo jazz music)

If you're gonna play both hands at the same time lead with your left hand because it actually, if your left hand is leading it, it's gonna actually take on a kind of a leadership role and be stronger, and it's actually gonna make itself stronger just by kind of forcing it to be in that position, so.

(slow tempo jazz music)

And only practice at the tempo where you can play comfortably with your left hand.  If you're a right-handed pianist generally your right hand's gonna be able to just shred through this stuff but, practice at the speed that you can play your left hand strong and confidently.  And you know, again, do all the same stuff with your right, take it through the keys.

(slow tempo jazz music)

Et cetera, Et cetera, but that's really it.  So, just do all the same stuff.  Practice playing melodies with your left hand and comping with your right.  Do everything you can to just switch it up.  And so, in that way you can build up your left hand little by little.

(upbeat jazz music)
